quote.p:
One example of these is when the Shaykh himself was stricken with a headache one day. He conceived the notion that some disease matter was trying to descend towards the membrane of his skull (
ḥijāb al-raʾs
) and that the occurrence of some sort of swelling was unavoidable. He had a great quantity of ice brought, crushed, and wrapped in a cloth and his head covered with the cloth. This was done so that the area gained strength and was protected from allowing the disease matter to enter and so the Shaykh recovered.

div.p:
He meant by his words ‘in prison’ the constipation of the belly from the colic with which he was afflicted, and by ‘the cure’ and ‘the salvation’ he meant the two books written by the Shaykh, and by this he intended poetic paronomasia (
jinās fī l-shiʿr
).

